I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data as the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the initial API fetch failed, I'll first try to validate the API endpoint using the network_validator tool before attempting to fetch data again. This will help identify if there are any issues with the API endpoint itself.

<tool_call>network_validator
{
  "schema": {},
  "data": {"url": "https://api.example.com/data"},
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the network_validator executed successfully, I'll now attempt to fetch the API data again using the network_fetcher tool, as the endpoint appears to be valid.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that we've successfully fetched the API data, I'll proceed with validating its structure using the data_processing_validator tool. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use an empty schema to perform basic validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {},
  "data": {"source": "https://api.example.com/data"},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since the data validation was successful, I'll now proceed with the data transformation step using the data_processing_transformer tool to convert the data into the required format.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "target_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since the data_processing_transformer timed out, I'll retry the operation with a longer timeout period to ensure the transformation completes successfully.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "target_format": "json",
  "timeout": 120,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
